What are Listed Agriculture Investments?
The listed agriculture sector includes companies involved in the production, processing, transporting, trading and marketing of soft commodities such as grains, meat, fish and forestry products, as well as those that supply products and services (including seeds, fertilizers, crop nutrients, agricultural equipment and water) to the agricultural industry. 

Why Invest in Listed Agriculture?
In today’s uncertain markets, listed agriculture assets can provide long-term growth potential and portfolio diversification to help investors reach their financial goals. Global population growth, increasing standards of living and scarcity of arable land are going to be the main drivers of growth for decades to come.
Agriculture as an Investment Opportunity
Demand Growth
It is estimated that world food production will need to increase between 60% to 90% by 2050 to meet the expected food demand.

Overall population growth - world’s population is estimated to reach 9 billion by 2050
Increasing standard of living will continue to increase food consumption in countries with large populations
Dietary shifts to higher protein foods such as meat require significantly more agricultural products

Growing Constraints

Slowing yield growth rates
Utilization rate of arable land is now at nearly 100% (with an exception of Sub-Saharan Africa)
Land loss caused by erosion, pollution and topsoil loss
Extreme weather creating both droughts and floods in key crop areas
Water scarcity – shrinking fresh water supply is coupled with increased demand (especially for protein crops)


Portfolio Selection Process
 




 
A combination top-down and bottom-up process


 
Macro views determine sector and regional allocations


 
Detailed company-level analysis is supported by a robust analytical framework






The manager seeks to find the securities that have the best prospects for above-average capital appreciation. 

 
Risk Mitigation
To mitigate risk, the manager follows a strict, repeatable stock selection process and sell discipline. Each security added to the portfolio has a sell target price; and each holding is monitored for any change in fundamentals, competitive positioning and investment thesis and the sell targets are adjusted accordingly.



Political and legislative risk
Corruption
High debt, large deficits, weak currencies





